                     <origDate notBefore="1880" notAfter="1950">Late 19th - first half of the 20th
                        cent.&#xD; Additio 1 mentions däğğač Kaśa, a son of rās Sǝbḥāt ʾAragāwi.
                        Däğğač Kaśa was the governor of ʿAgamä in 1914-1918 and 1941-1948. Cp. Hagos
                        Gabra Yoḥannǝs, “Political History of Tigray: Rivalry for power (1910-1935),
                        PhD thesis, Addis Abäba University, 2003, 46.</origDate>
                  </origin>
               <provenance>Walda ʾAragāwi is the name inserted in some
                     supplication formulas at the end of the commemoration entries (or elsewhere
                     filling the lines) by a different hand, in reddish-brown ink (s. 35ra, l.22; 35vc, l.33; 36vb, l.35; 36vb, l.35; 57rb,
                     l.10; 105rb, l.5; 177vb, l.6). Walda ʾAragāwi is so far unidentified; his
                     relation to däğğač Kaśa of Additio 1 is unclear (possibly, it is Kaśa's
                     baptismal name). däğğač Kaśa Sǝbḥāt, according to Additio
                     1.</provenance></history>
